    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-09T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-09T02:00:00-05:00" n="1314"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1314">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860C.01/12–944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-09T10:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 9, 1944—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 9—9:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4715. An American correspondent who had an interview today with Bierut, President
                    of the Polish National Council, was told by the latter that the Polish National
                    Council [would] meet in Lublin on December 16<note n="23" xml:id="d1314fn23"
                        >This meeting was postponed to December 30, 1944.</note> in order to
                    consider the question of declaring the National Committee of Liberation to be
                    the provisional government of Poland.</p>
                <p>Bierut said that the Lublin Poles considered that there was no longer any chance
                    of an agreement with the London government. Mikolajczyk could come back
                    personally, if he so wished, as a leader of the Peasant Party; but he would of
                    course have to be prepared to recognize and abide by the provisions of the 1921
                        constitution.<note n="24" xml:id="d1314fn24">The democratic constitution of
                        March 17, 1921.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to Department as No. 4715, repeated to London for Schoenfeld as No. 295.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
